<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40031d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40031d">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40031d"> 31(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ cultivators</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the Telugu-speaking area of the Deccan (the Andhra country) this difficulty <font color="green">[of movement of people]</font> has manifested itself in connexion with the simultaneous movement among the two great sections of the outcastes called the <i>Malas</i> and <i>Madigas</i>. Of all the present-day mass movements in India this is now in fullest flood. Malas are agricultural labourers, and some of them weave coarse cloth in the agricultural off-seasons. Madigas are primarily workers in leather, though they also are cultivators. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI1"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 33-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
